nutes and discard supernatant to get rid of liquid medium.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":172800,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":600},{"id":1158234,"guid":"89B6100097E411EBA6F49F2F1C8EAD6E","previous_id":1151021,"previous_guid":"8F2481408E0F11EBAF8F85232E6B751B","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"67E7CB3812234224942F72D56A5BFB0D","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Histone protein extraction"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"A5637F3013CC49709B62129186BFED4E","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Centrifuge at 3,250 xg for 20 minutes at 4 \u2103, and discard supernatant.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":86400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":1200},{"id":1158762,"guid":"BF521BC0985A11EB92018BB44782B229","previous_id":1151020,"previous_guid":"8F22AC818E0F11EBAF8F85232E6B751B","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"859A05933FD843F5B9B91F75C8CF6CF3","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Histone protein extraction"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"BEFD48C677684902ACA2F4333D7BFC7F","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Resuspend in 1 mL ice-cold PBS buffer.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":86400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":60}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Mass spectrometry is a powerful technique to uncover histone post-translational modifications in an unbiased and quantitative manner (Noberini,<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">et al<\/span><span>.,The FEBS Journal, 2021).\u00a0Yet, such analyses require good quality protein samples, a challenge when working with fungi. Here, we\u00a0present\u00a0a protocol based on the work by Noberini and colleagues (Noberini, <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">et al<\/span><span>., Methods, 2020) to\u00a0extract histone\u00a0proteins\u00a0from filamentous fungi\u00a0for applications like mass spectrometry-based analyses of post-translational modifications. Several modifications were made: 1) additional cell disruption and homogenization steps\u00a0using\u00a0freeze-drying and TissueLyser II; 2) increased Triton X-100 concentration in the lysis buffer; and 3) prolonged incubation time in lysis buffer. This protocol is reproducible, and the proteins extracted from three\u00a0<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Aspergillus<\/span><span>\u00a0species (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">A. niger<\/span><span>,\u00a0<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">A. fumigatus,<\/span><span>\u00a0and\u00a0<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">A. nidulans<\/span><span>)\u00a0were\u00a0of good quality for mass spectrometry.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1621234987}